  "text": "This seven-year surveillance study demonstrated the changing molecular epidemiology of C. difficile in Texas, and identified the emergence of a novel ribotype 255. Although overall patterns were similar to those seen in national U.S. data, ribotype 014-020 was uniquely the most common ribotype seen in Texas, and differences in infecting strains were noted when stratifying our population by age. Evidence provided by this surveillance helps expand our understanding of C. difficile epidemiology in the U.S. and emphasizes the importance of continued efforts. Continued efforts toward more wide-spread surveillance in the United States should be emphasized as the rate of CDI continues to increase nationally, despite significant infection control and antimicrobial stewardship efforts [CITATION_1] .",
